[30;1m16 | [0m[35m(see `Cubed's documentation <https://cubed-dev.github.io/cubed/>`_ and the `cubed-xarray package <ht[0m

[30;1m725 | [0m[35m                    # we can equivalently leave them as slices aknd transpose[0m
[30;1m726 | [0m[35m                    # the result. This is significantly faster/more efficient[0m
[30;1m727 | [0m[35m                    # for most array backends.[0m

[30;1m6423 | [0m[35m- :py:func:`~xarray.concat` was computing variables that aren't in memory[0m

[30;1m616 | [0m[35mComparing Trees for Isomorphism[0m
[30;1m617 | [0m[35m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~[0m
[30;1m618 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m619 | [0m[35mFor it to make sense to map a single non-unary function over the nodes of multiple trees at once,[0m
[30;1m620 | [0m[35meach tree needs to have the same structure. Specifically two trees can only be considered similar,[0m
[30;1m621 | [0m[35mor "isomorphic", if the full paths to all of their descendent nodes are the same.[0m
[30;1m622 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m775 | [0m[35mCoordinate variables are inherited to descendent nodes, which is only possible because[0m
[30;1m776 | [0m[35mvariables at different levels of a hierarchical DataTree are always[0m
[30;1m777 | [0m[35maligned. Placing the ``time`` variable at the root node automatically indicates[0m
[30;1m778 | [0m[35mthat it applies to all descendent nodes. Similarly, ``station`` is in the base[0m
[30;1m779 | [0m[35m``weather`` node, because it applies to all weather variables, both directly in[0m
[30;1m780 | [0m[35m``weather`` and in the ``temperature`` sub-tree.  Notice the inherited coordinates are[0m

[30;1m537 | [0m[35mEach child automatically knows about its parent node, and a node without a[0m
[30;1m538 | [0m[35mparent is known as a "root" node (represented by the ``parent`` attribute[0m
[30;1m539 | [0m[35mpointing to ``None``). Nodes can have multiple children, but as each child node[0m
[30;1m540 | [0m[35mhas at most one parent, there can only ever be one root node in a given tree.[0m
[30;1m541 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m542 | [0m[35mThe overall structure is technically a connected acyclic undirected rooted graph,[0m
[30;1m543 | [0m[35motherwise known as a `"Tree" <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_(graph_theory)>`_.[0m

[30;1m705 | [0m[35m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~[0m
[30;1m706 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m707 | [0m[35mDataTree implements a simple inheritance mechanism. Coordinates, dimensions and their[0m
[30;1m708 | [0m[35massociated indices are propagated from downward starting from the root node to[0m
[30;1m709 | [0m[35mall descendent nodes.  Coordinate inheritance was inspired by the NetCDF-CF[0m
[30;1m710 | [0m[35minherited dimensions, but DataTree's inheritance is slightly stricter yet[0m
[30;1m711 | [0m[35measier to reason about.[0m

[30;1m694 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m695 | [0m[35mIf you copy a :py:class:`~xarray.DataTree` using the :py:func:`copy` function or the[0m
[30;1m696 | [0m[35m:py:meth:`xarray.DataTree.copy` method it will copy the subtree,[0m
[30;1m697 | [0m[35mmeaning that node and children below it, but no parents above it.[0m
[30;1m698 | [0m[35mLike for :py:class:`~xarray.Dataset`, this copy is shallow by default, but you can copy all the[0m
[30;1m699 | [0m[35munderlying data arrays by calling ``dt.copy(deep=True)``.[0m

[30;1m552 | [0m[35mCreating a DataTree[0m
[30;1m553 | [0m[35m~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~[0m
[30;1m554 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m555 | [0m[35mOne way to create a :py:class:`~xarray.DataTree` from scratch is to create each node individually,[0m

[30;1m557 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m558 | [0m[35mThe :py:class:`~xarray.DataTree` constructor takes:[0m

[30;1m699 | [0m[35mThe object returned, ``g`` in the above examples, is a :py:class:`~xarray.plot.FacetGrid` object[0m
[30;1m700 | [0m[35mthat links a :py:class:`DataArray` to a matplotlib figure with a particular structure.[0m
[30;1m701 | [0m[35mThis object can be used to control the behavior of the multiple plots.[0m
[30;1m702 | [0m[35mIt borrows an API and code from `Seaborn's FacetGrid[0m
[30;1m703 | [0m[35m<https://seaborn.pydata.org/tutorial/axis_grids.html>`_.[0m
[30;1m704 | [0m[35mThe structure is contained within the ``axs`` and ``name_dicts``[0m
